  <!-- ⑧ COMMON MISTAKES -->
  <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common MCB Sizing Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
  <p>These are the five most expensive and most dangerous errors made during MCB selection:</p>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Upsizing the MCB without upgrading the wire</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">
        The single most dangerous residential electrical mistake. A tripping 16A breaker protects
        2.5 mm² cable. Swapping it for a 32A breaker means that cable — rated for about 18–20A —
        is now "protected" by a device that won't trip until 32A flows through it. At 30A, the wire
        overheats invisibly inside your wall. You won't notice until the insulation ignites.
        The fix is always to resolve the cause of tripping, not to override the protection.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Using Type B on all motor circuits</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">
        Type B breakers are cheap and ubiquitous. Many electricians install them everywhere for
        simplicity. But on AC and pump circuits, the motor's starting inrush will trip a B-curve
        breaker immediately — every single time. The homeowner then calls an electrician, who
        either raises the breaker rating (dangerous) or replaces it with the correct Type C
        (the right fix). Specifying Type C upfront costs ₹0 extra in planning and prevents
        months of frustrating nuisance trips.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Skipping the 1.25 safety margin on continuous loads</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">
        A geyser, room heater, or server UPS running for hours is a continuous load. The IEC
        60898 rule exists because MCBs accumulate internal heat over time under sustained current.
        An MCB running at exactly its rated current for 3+ hours can drift into trip territory
        even without any fault. The 1.25 factor (design to 80% capacity) gives thermal headroom
        so the breaker runs cool and stable. Skipping it on long-running loads is asking for
        nuisance trips at the worst possible time.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Running multiple heavy appliances on a single shared socket circuit</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">
        A room's general-purpose socket circuit is typically sized for 1,000–2,000W of
        diversified load (TV, phone chargers, laptops). The moment you add a room heater
        or high-powered device, you've crossed the circuit's design load. Heavy appliances —
        geysers, ACs, washing machines, water heaters — must each have their own dedicated
        circuit and MCB, not share a general socket ring.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Buying no-brand MCBs to save ₹50</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">
        The MCB is the last line of defence between your wiring and a fire. No-brand MCBs from
        unverified manufacturers are frequently mis-calibrated — they may trip at the wrong
        current, fail to trip at all under a short circuit, or degrade rapidly. A Schneider,
        Legrand, Siemens, ABB, or Hager MCB costs ₹120–250 depending on rating. This is not
        a component to optimise for price. The ₹180 price difference between a quality MCB
        and a counterfeit one is irrelevant against the value of the wiring, the appliances,
        and the building it is protecting.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ⑨ FAQS -->
  <KnowledgeHubCTA id="use-the-calculator" />

  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="kh-faq">
    <details>
      <summary>
        What is the standard MCB rating for a 1.5 Ton AC?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        A 1.5 Ton split AC draws 1,500–1,800W (6.5–8A) during continuous operation. After the 1.25
        safety margin, the design current is about 8–10A — which points to a 10A MCB mathematically.
        However, the compressor's starting surge (inrush) can hit 30–40A for 0.1–0.3 seconds.
        A 10A breaker — even Type C — will trip on that surge. The industry-standard recommendation
        is a <strong>16A Type C MCB on a dedicated 2.5 mm² circuit</strong>. This provides both
        adequate continuous protection and enough surge tolerance for the compressor to start cleanly.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Can one MCB protect two rooms?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Yes — for lighting circuits, one MCB commonly serves multiple rooms. A 6A lighting MCB can
        protect the lights in an entire flat if the total wattage stays within 1,380W (6A × 230V).
        For power socket circuits, it is poor practice to loop two rooms through one MCB if heavy
        appliances are likely to be used, because a fault or overload in one room will cut power
        to both. Modern wiring practice gives each room (or at least each high-load zone) its own
        dedicated circuit for exactly this reason.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Can I use a 32A MCB to run my 1.5 HP water pump?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        No — a 32A MCB is dangerously oversized for a 1.5 HP pump, which draws only about 4.8A
        continuously. A 32A breaker provides almost no meaningful protection against an internal
        winding fault or cable overload at 5–10A. The wiring and pump windings can overheat
        significantly before a 32A breaker reacts. Use a <strong>16A Type C MCB</strong> on
        2.5 mm² cable — the 16A rating absorbs the inrush surge while still providing real
        protection at currents well above the 4.8A running load.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Does MCB rating affect my electricity bill?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        No. An MCB is a switch — it draws no power itself and has zero effect on your bill.
        Your electricity meter measures the energy (kWh) consumed by your appliances, not the
        capacity of your breakers. A 63A main breaker does not "use" more electricity than a 32A one.
        What does affect your bill is the sanctioned load limit set by your utility — if your
        demand consistently exceeds the sanctioned limit, the utility may apply a higher tariff
        or demand charges. This is a metering and tariff issue, not an MCB issue.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What is the difference between a B curve and C curve MCB?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        The curve type defines the magnetic (instantaneous) trip threshold — how many times the
        rated current must be exceeded before the breaker trips in milliseconds. Type B trips at
        3–5× rated current, making it fast and sensitive — ideal for circuits where you want the
        fastest possible response to a fault (lighting, pure resistive loads). Type C trips at
        5–10× rated current, giving enough tolerance for motor inrush surges (ACs, pumps,
        refrigerators) to pass without triggering a trip. Same ampere rating, very different
        behaviour during a surge event. Both are valid choices — in the right place.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Why does my MCB trip when I turn on the geyser?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Three possibilities, in order of likelihood:
        <ol class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm list-decimal list-inside">
          <li><strong>Overloaded circuit:</strong> The geyser is sharing a circuit with other heavy loads (washing machine, heater). Run the geyser on a dedicated circuit.</li>
          <li><strong>Undersized MCB:</strong> A 3,000W geyser at 230V draws 13A. With the safety margin that's 16.25A — a 16A MCB will trip. You need a 20A MCB and 4 mm² cable.</li>
          <li><strong>Faulty heating element:</strong> An internal short in the element causes the breaker to trip instantly. The element must be tested and replaced by a plumber/electrician.</li>
        </ol>
        For a deeper diagnostic guide, see our article on
        <a href="/knowledge-hub/mcb-sizing/why-does-my-mcb-keep-tripping" class="text-accent hover:underline">why MCBs keep tripping</a>.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        How do I know what gauge wire is currently in my walls?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        The safest approach is to check the wiring at the distribution panel — the cables connecting
        to each MCB should have their cross-section printed on the outer insulation jacket
        (e.g., <code>2.5 mm² FR PVC</code>). If it's not visible, look at your home's electrical
        layout drawings (if available), or ask the original electrician. As a general rule of thumb
        for homes built after 1990 in India: power socket circuits use 2.5 mm², lighting uses
        1.5 mm², and sub-DB feeders use 6 mm² or larger. If you are unsure, have a licensed
        electrician inspect before changing any MCB ratings.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Is it safe to install an MCB myself without an electrician?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Working inside a distribution panel carries genuine risk — the incoming supply (from the
        utility meter to the main switch) is always live, even when all individual MCBs are off.
        Touching the busbars or incomer terminals with wet or uninsulated hands on a live panel
        can be fatal. In India, electrical work on distribution boards legally requires a licensed
        electrician in most states. Beyond legality: an incorrectly installed MCB — wrong orientation,
        loose terminal, wrong rating — can be far more dangerous than the original problem. For
        like-for-like MCB replacement on an already-isolated circuit, a careful DIYer can manage.
        For anything involving rewiring, adding circuits, or main board work, use a professional.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

